KRISHNA_YAJURVEDA_K1_P2 = {
    1: {
        "sanskrit": "रक्षसां वा एषा यज्ञियानामनुक्ता यद्वा अग्निहोत्रं यज्ञमुखं जुहोति तद्रक्षसामनुक्तानां यज्ञियानां प्रायश्चित्तिराहुतिरेका त्वष्टुः पुत्रस्य वा इन्द्रशत्रुर्वृत्र आसीद्यद्वा इन्द्रो वृत्रं हत्वा ब्रह्महत्याममन्यत तदेनं यज्ञो ब्रह्महत्यायै निरवदयत तस्मादाहुर्नेन्द्रस्य ब्रह्महत्यां गच्छतीति ब्रह्महत्याया एवैतत्प्रायश्चित्तिर्यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोति ब्रह्महत्यामेवास्य तेनापहन्ति ॥",
        "meaning": "The enemies that lie in wait for the sacrifice are the Raksases. When he offers the Agnihotra at the beginning of the sacrifice, that is the atonement for the Raksases that lie in wait. One oblation is for the son of Tvashtr, Vritra, the foe of Indra. When Indra had slain Vritra, he thought he had committed a slaying of a Brahman. The sacrifice freed him from the guilt of Brahman-slaying. Therefore they say, 'Indra incurs not the guilt of Brahman-slaying.' This is the atonement for the guilt of Brahman-slaying; when he offers this Agnihotra offering, he thereby removes from him the guilt of Brahman-slaying.",
        "example": "The Raksases are your inner resistances. One resistance you face today. Not avoid. Face. That facing is the atonement. Indra's guilt is the heaviness after any act of destruction — even necessary destruction. One necessary ending today. A habit. A relationship. A phase. End it without guilt. Not because guilt is wrong. Because the sacrifice of ending is also sacred."
    },
    2: {
        "sanskrit": "अग्निं ब्रह्महत्याया अवृणीत सा वै पुनर्मृत्युः स पुनर्मृत्युना समवदत सो ऽग्निरब्रवीत् पुनर्मृत्यो मा मोपवद्स्था यजमानाय ब्रह्महत्यामपहनानीति तस्मादग्निरपहन्ति यजमानाद्ब्रह्महत्याम् । यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोति ब्रह्महत्यामेवास्य तेनापहन्ति । वायुं ब्रह्महत्याया अवृणीत सा वै पुनर्मृत्युः स पुनर्मृत्युना समवदत स वायुरब्रवीत् पुनर्मृत्यो मा मोपवद्स्था यजमानाय ब्रह्महत्यामपहनानीति तस्माद्वायुरपहन्ति यजमानाद्ब्रह्महत्याम् । यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोति ब्रह्महत्यामेवास्य तेनापहन्ति । सूर्यं ब्रह्महत्याया अवृणीत सा वै पुनर्मृत्युः स पुनर्मृत्युना समवदत स सूर्योऽब्रवीत् पुनर्मृत्यो मा मोपवद्स्था यजमानाय ब्रह्महत्यामपहनानीति तस्मात्सूर्योऽपहन्ति यजमानाद्ब्रह्महत्याम् । यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोति ब्रह्महत्यामेवास्य तेनापहन्ति ॥",
        "meaning": "Agni was chosen for the guilt of Brahman-slaying. That guilt is death renewed. He spoke with death renewed. Agni said, 'Let me not be joined with thee, death renewed; let me remove from the sacrificer the guilt of Brahman-slaying.' Therefore Agni removes from the sacrificer the guilt of Brahman-slaying. When he offers this Agnihotra offering, he thereby removes from him the guilt of Brahman-slaying. Vayu was chosen for the guilt of Brahman-slaying... Surya was chosen for the guilt of Brahman-slaying...",
        "example": "Agni (fire/will), Vayu (breath/energy), Surya (sun/awareness) — all three remove guilt when you act. One action from will, breath, and awareness together. That action removes the heaviness of past mistakes. Not by forgetting. By integrating. Death renewed is the cycle of repeating the same mistake. One pattern broken today. That breaking is death renewed defeated."
    },
    3: {
        "sanskrit": "आयुर्ह वा एष आत्मनस्पृणक्ति यः पुरा सूर्योदयादग्निहोत्रं जुहोति यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोत्यायुरेवास्य तेन स्पृणक्ति । पशून् ह वा एष आत्मनः प्रयच्छति यः पुरा सूर्योदयादग्निहोत्रं जुहोति यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोति पशूनेवास्य तेन प्रयच्छति । प्रजां ह वा एष आत्मनः प्रजनयति यः पुरा सूर्योदयादग्निहोत्रं जुहोति यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोति प्रजामेवास्य तेन प्रजनयति । यशो ह वा एष आत्मनः प्रथयति यः पुरा सूर्योदयादग्निहोत्रं जुहोति यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोति यश एवास्य तेन प्रथयति । ब्रह्मवर्चसं ह वा एष आत्मन इन्द्धे यः पुरा सूर्योदयादग्निहोत्रं जुहोति यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोति ब्रह्मवर्चसमेवास्य तेन इन्धे । इन्द्रो ह वा एष आत्मनः सहो बिभर्ति यः पुरा सूर्योदयादग्निहोत्रं जुहोति यद्वा एतमग्निहोत्रहोमं जुहोत्यिन्द्रियमेवास्य तेन सहो बिभर्ति ॥",
        "meaning": "He who offers the Agnihotra before sunrise draws to himself life. When he offers this Agnihotra offering, he thereby draws to himself life. He who offers before sunrise gives to himself cattle... produces for himself offspring... spreads abroad his own glory... kindles for himself spiritual lustre... bears for himself the might of Indra.",
        "example": "Before sunrise means before the noise of the world begins. One action done in early morning silence today. That action draws life, not just productivity. Cattle are your resources. Offspring are your creative projects. Glory is not fame — it is integrity. Spiritual lustre is the light in your eyes when you act from truth. Indra's might is the courage to act when you are afraid. One early action contains all five gifts. Not because it is special. Because it is first."
    },
    4: {
        "sanskrit": "अग्निहोत्रं जुहोत्यग्नये वैश्वानराय ब्रह्मवर्चसकामो ब्रह्मवर्चस्येव भवति । अग्निहोत्रं जुहोत्यग्नये वैश्वानराय यशस्कामो यशस्व्येव भवति । अग्निहोत्रं जुहोत्यग्नये वैश्वानराय प्रजाकामः प्रजावानेव भवति । अग्निहोत्रं जुहोत्यग्नये वैश्वानराय पशुकामः पशुमानेव भवति । अग्निहोत्रं जुहोत्यग्नये वैश्वानराय स्वर्गकामः स्वर्गमेव लोकं याति । अग्निहोत्रं जुहोत्यग्नये वैश्वानराय ब्रह्मणा वर्चसा समर्ध्यते स यावदग्निहोत्रं जुहोति तावद्ध वा आयुषो न मीयते । दीर्घमायुरेति य एवं विद्वानग्निहोत्रं जुहोति ॥",
        "meaning": "He who desires spiritual lustre offers the Agnihotra to Agni Vaisvanara; he becomes endowed with spiritual lustre. He who desires glory offers... he becomes glorious. He who desires offspring offers... he becomes rich in offspring. He who desires cattle offers... he becomes rich in cattle. He who desires the heavenly world offers... he goes to the heavenly world. He who offers the Agnihotra to Agni Vaisvanara is endowed with Brahman's splendour; so long as he offers the Agnihotra he does not lose any of his life; he attains long life who knowing thus offers the Agnihotra.",
        "example": "Agni Vaisvanara is the fire that belongs to all humanity. One action done not for your benefit alone. For all. That action is the offering. Spiritual lustre is not a glow. It is the clarity that comes from serving the whole. Not fame. Service. Glory is not applause. It is the quiet satisfaction of right action. One action for the whole today. That action contains all desires — not because you get them, but because you stop needing them."
    },
    5: {
        "sanskrit": "इन्द्रो ह वृत्राय वज्रमुदयच्छत्तस्मादिन्द्रियं वीर्यं वज्रः सो ऽग्निरभवत्तस्मादग्निर्वज्रो यदग्निहोत्रं जुहोति वज्रमेव तत्समिन्धे स एतं वज्रं समिद्धं सन्तं यजमानाय प्रयच्छति स यावदग्निहोत्रं जुहोति तावता वै स वज्रेण द्विषतो भ्रातृव्यस्य वीर्यं प्रति मुञ्चति । यद्वै प्रातरग्निहोत्रं जुहोति तेन यज्ञस्य शिरः कल्पयति यत्सायं जुहोति तेन यज्ञस्य पश्चादर्धं कल्पयति । प्रातरग्निहोत्रेण वा इन्द्रो वृत्राय प्रत्यवदत सायमग्निहोत्रेण वृत्रं प्रत्यवदत् तस्मात्प्रातरग्निहोत्रं जुहुयात्सायमग्निहोत्रं जुहुयाद्यदेकं जुहुयादेकत एनं वज्रः प्रति मुञ्चेदथो द्विषन्तमेव भ्रातृव्यं करोति यदुभे जुहोति तेनेतरेतरतो वज्रं परिगृह्य तिष्ठति । अमुं चामुष्य पुत्रमिति ब्रूयात् तं वज्रः प्रति मुञ्चति यं द्वेष्टि तस्मै ब्रूयात्तेनैनं वज्रेण निर्भजति स सपत्नक्षयणो वा एष यज्ञो यदग्निहोत्रम् । प्रजाक्षयणो वा एष यज्ञो यदग्निहोत्रं पशुक्षयणो वा एष यज्ञो यदग्निहोत्रम् । आयुष्क्षयणो वा एष यज्ञो यदग्निहोत्रम् । स्वर्गस्य लोकस्य क्षयणो वा एष यज्ञो यदग्निहोत्रम् ॥",
        "meaning": "Indra raised his thunderbolt against Vritra; therefore the thunderbolt is Indra's might and power. That thunderbolt became Agni; therefore Agni is the thunderbolt. When he offers the Agnihotra, he kindles the thunderbolt; having kindled it, he gives it to the sacrificer. So long as he offers the Agnihotra, with that thunderbolt he repels the power of his foe and rival. With the morning Agnihotra he fashions the head of the sacrifice; with the evening Agnihotra he fashions the hinder part of the sacrifice. With the morning offering Indra smote down on Vritra; with the evening offering he smote Vritra. Therefore one should offer the morning and the evening Agnihotra; if he offer only one, the thunderbolt would smite him on one side, and he would make his foe his rival; if he offer both, he stands holding the thunderbolt on both sides. He should say, 'To N.N., the son of N.N.' The thunderbolt smites him whom he hates; for him he should say it; with that thunderbolt he rends him. This sacrifice, the Agnihotra, is the destroyer of rivals, of offspring, of cattle, of life, of the heavenly world.",
        "example": "Thunderbolt is your decisive action. One decision made without hesitation today. That decision is the thunderbolt. Not force. Decisiveness. Morning offering is your first action of the day. Evening offering is your last reflection. One day with both: act first, reflect last. That day holds the thunderbolt on both sides. Not one without the other. The destroyer of rivals means your old patterns are destroyed. Not people. Patterns. One pattern destroyed by decisive action today. That destruction is not violence. It is liberation."
    },
    6: {
        "sanskrit": "प्रातरग्निहोत्रं जुहोति सायमग्निहोत्रं जुहोति तेन वै स एतं यज्ञं न व्यथयति य एवं विद्वानग्निहोत्रं जुहोति । प्रजापतिः प्रजा असृजत ता अस्मात् सृष्टाः पराचीः प्राणन् ता अग्निरन्वायत्ता मृत्युना पर्यगृह्णात् सोऽग्निरब्रवीदहमिदं मिथुन्यानीति ता अग्निर्मिथुन्यायत् तासां य एवं विद्वानग्निहोत्रं जुहोति मिथुन्यानीवैव तेन प्रजया पशुभिर्मिथुन्यान् भवति । प्रजापतिः प्रजा असृजत ता अस्मात् सृष्टाः प्राचीः प्राणन् ता अग्निरन्वायत्ता मृत्युना पर्यगृह्णात् सोऽग्निरब्रवीदहमिदं प्रजनयानीति ता अग्निः प्रजनयत् तासां य एवं विद्वानग्निहोत्रं जुहोति प्रजनयितैव तेन प्रजया पशुभिः प्रजनयिता भवति । प्रजापतिः प्रजा असृजत ता अस्मात् सृष्टा अवाञ्चः प्राणन् ता अग्निरन्वायत्ता मृत्युना पर्यगृह्णात् सोऽग्निरब्रवीदहमिदमुपजीवानीति ता अग्निरुपाजीवत् तासां य एवं विद्वानग्निहोत्रं जुहोत्युपजीवितैव तेन प्रजया पशुभिरुपजीविता भवति ॥",
        "meaning": "He who offers the morning and evening Agnihotra does not disturb this sacrifice. Prajapati created creatures; they departed from him breathing forth. Agni, following them, encompassed them with death. Agni said, 'Let me pair them.' He paired them. He who knowing thus offers the Agnihotra becomes a layer of his offspring and cattle. Prajapati created creatures... Agni said, 'Let me beget them.' He begot them. He who knowing thus offers the Agnihotra becomes a begetter of offspring and cattle. Prajapati created creatures... Agni said, 'Let me support them.' He supported them. He who knowing thus offers the Agnihotra becomes a supporter of offspring and cattle.",
        "example": "Prajapati is your creative source. Creatures are your ideas, projects, actions. They depart from you when not attended. Agni (your will) follows them and can either pair (connect), beget (create), or support (sustain). One idea you have neglected. Attend to it today. Your will can pair it with action, beget a new form, or support its growth. Not all three at once. One. Choose. Agni's role is not to do everything. It is to choose which relationship to have with each creation."
    },
    7: {
        "sanskrit": "प्रजापतिः प्रजा असृजत तासु सृष्टासु देवाः प्राजापत्या यज्ञमतन्वत तस्य पुरस्तादग्निर्गायत्रेण छन्दसोपधावत् तमग्नये गायत्राय छागलो निरवदयत तस्य वै गायत्रो वा एष छागलो यदग्निः समिध्येत हि स प्रातरग्निहोत्रमाज्यभागौ जुहोति तेन वै स एनमग्नये गायत्राय छागलेन समर्धयति । तस्य दक्षिणत इन्द्रो वै त्रैष्टुभेन छन्दसोपधावत् तमिन्द्राय त्रैष्टुभाय मेषी निरवदयत तस्य वै त्रैष्टुभो वा एष मेषो यदिन्द्रः प्रच्यवेत हि स मध्यन्दिने सवनमुपयन्ति तेन वै स एनमिन्द्राय त्रैष्टुभाय मेष्या समर्धयति । तस्य पश्चाद्विश्वे देवा वै जागतेन छन्दसोपधावन् तान्विश्वेभ्यो देवेभ्यो जागतेभ्यो गौर्निरवदयत तस्य वै जागतो वा एष गौर्विश्वे देवाः सायमग्निहोत्रमाज्यभागौ जुहोति तेन वै स एनान्विश्वेभ्यो देवेभ्यो जागतेभ्यो गवा समर्धयति । तस्योत्तरतो वरुणो विराजा छन्दसोपधावत् तं वरुणाय विराजे बस्तो निरवदयत तस्य वै राजन्यो वा एष बस्तो यद्वरुणः स एष पशूनां वरुणगृहीतो यो राजन्यः कामयेत पशुमान् स्यामिति स बस्तेन यजेत तेन वै स एनं वरुणाय विराजे बस्तेन समर्धयति । तस्य मध्यतो बृहस्पतिरनुष्टुभा छन्दसोपधावत् तं बृहस्पतयेऽनुष्टुभाय मेषो निरवदयत तस्य वै ब्राह्मणो वा एष मेषो यद्बृहस्पतिः स एष पशूनां ब्रह्मगृहीतो यो ब्राह्मणः कामयेत पशुमान् स्यामिति स मेषेण यजेत तेन वै स एनं बृहस्पतयेऽनुष्टुभाय मेषेण समर्धयति । तस्य सर्वतो देवाः पङ्क्त्या छन्दसोपधावन् तान्देवेभ्यः पाङ्क्तेभ्योऽश्वो निरवदयत तस्य वै पाङ्क्तो वा एषोऽश्वो यद्देवास्तस्मादश्वमेधेन यजेत यः कामयेत सर्वान् कामानाप्नुयामिति सर्वान् हैव कामानाप्नोति योऽश्वमेधेन यजते ॥",
        "meaning": "Prajapati created creatures; when they were created, the gods, children of Prajapati, performed the sacrifice. From the east Agni approached with the Gayatri metre; to Agni of the Gayatri was assigned the goat. From the south Indra approached with the Tristubh metre; to Indra of the Tristubh was assigned the ewe. From the west the All-gods approached with the Jagati metre; to the All-gods of the Jagati was assigned the cow. From the north Varuna approached with the Virat metre; to Varuna of the Virat was assigned the he-goat. From the centre Brhaspati approached with the Anustubh metre; to Brhaspati of the Anustubh was assigned the ram. From all sides the gods approached with the Pankti metre; to the gods of the Pankti was assigned the horse. Therefore he who desires to attain all desires should sacrifice with the horse sacrifice; he indeed attains all desires who sacrifices with the horse sacrifice.",
        "example": "The five directions and five metres correspond to your five senses and five elements. East (sight), South (hearing), West (taste), North (touch), Centre (smell). Each sense has its offering. One sense brought under conscious control today. Not suppressed. Controlled. The goat, ewe, cow, he-goat, ram, horse are not animals. They are the energies of each sense. Sight's goat is discernment. Hearing's ewe is listening. Taste's cow is nourishment. Touch's he-goat is boundaries. Smell's ram is intuition. All senses together, the horse, is integrated awareness. One moment of integrated awareness — seeing, hearing, tasting, touching, smelling all at once. That moment is the horse sacrifice. It attains all desires because desire itself is transcended in presence."
    },
    8: {
        "sanskrit": "पुरुषं वा एतं यज्ञमन्वाहुः पुरुषमेव यज्ञमन्वाहुः । तस्य यानि प्रथमानि कर्माणि तानि पुरोडाशा द्वितीयानि पशवस्तृतीयानि पशुबन्धा यानि परमकर्माणि ते सोमास्तं वा एतं यज्ञं प्रजापतिरात्मन्नात्मन्नकल्पयत् स येन येनात्मना यज्ञो यज्ञेन समकल्पत तेन तेन प्रजापतिरभवत् । स वा एष प्रजापतिर्य एवं वेद । अथो आहुर्यज्ञ एव प्रजापतिः । तस्य ये यजमानाः स प्रजापतिर्य एवं वेद । तस्य यानि हवींषि तत्प्रजापतेः शरीरं य एवं वेद । तस्य यानि वषट्काराणि स यज्ञस्य मुखं य एवं वेद । तस्य यानि स्वाहाकाराणि तं प्रजापतेर्घोषं य एवं वेद ॥",
        "meaning": "Verily, the sacrifice they call the man; the sacrifice they call the man. His first rites are the rice cakes; his second are the victims; his third are the animal sacrifices; his highest rites are the Soma offerings. Prajapati arranged this sacrifice in his own self; with whatever self the sacrifice was arranged with the sacrifice, with that Prajapati became. He verily is Prajapati who knows thus. And they say, 'The sacrifice is Prajapati.' His sacrificers are Prajapati; he who knows thus is Prajapati. His offerings are the body of Prajapati; he who knows thus is Prajapati. His Vashat calls are the mouth of the sacrifice; he who knows thus is Prajapati. His Swaha calls are the voice of Prajapati; he who knows thus is Prajapati.",
        "example": "You are the sacrifice. Not a metaphor. You. Your first actions are the rice cakes — small offerings of attention. Your sustained efforts are the victims — what you give your time to. Your boundaries are the animal sacrifices — what you release. Your highest actions are the Soma offerings — actions done with full presence, no distraction. One action at each level today. Small attention. Sustained effort. Clear boundary. Full presence. That one action in each category makes you Prajapati — lord of creatures, master of your own creations. Not lord over others. Lord over your own scattered energies."
    },
    9: {
        "sanskrit": "प्रजापतिर्ह वै पशूनामीशे स एतं पशुबन्धमपश्यत् तं देवा अन्वजानन् यद्वै पशुबन्धेन पशूनप्नुवीति ततो वै ते पशूनप्नुवत ये पशुबन्धेन यजन्ते । एष वै प्रथमः पशुबन्धो यदग्नीषोमीयः पशुः प्राणो वा एष यदग्नीषोमीयः पशुः प्राणेन ह वा एष पशूनप्नोति योऽग्नीषोमीयेन पशुना यजते यदग्नीषोमीयः पशुरारम्भणीयो भवति प्रज्ञात्यै प्रजननाय । तं वा एतं पशुं सांतपनं सांतपनं वा एतत्पशुबन्धस्य यदुत्सर्गः पशोर्यो वै प्रथमं पशुबन्धं प्रयुङ्क्ते म्रियत एव यो द्वितीयं य एतमेव प्रयुङ्क्ते स जीवति तस्मादेतमेव प्रयुञ्जीत न प्रथमं न द्वितीयम् । शिरः पशोः प्रथमा ग्रहीतव्या यदि शिरो गृह्णीयात् प्राणमेवास्य गृह्णीयात् तस्मान्न गृह्णीयात् पश्चाच्छिरः प्रच्छिद्य प्रहरेत् । अथो आहुर्य एव मध्यतो गृह्णीयात् स यज्ञक्रयुर्भवति तस्मान्मध्यत एव गृह्णीयात् । प्राणा वै मध्यतः प्राणानामवरुद्ध्यै । अथो आहुः प्रजापतिर्वै पशुः प्रजापतेर्ह वा एष प्रियं धाम भवति यं पशुमुपाकरोति तस्मात्पशुमुपाकुर्यात् ॥",
        "meaning": "Prajapati ruled over the cattle. He saw this animal sacrifice; the gods approved it, thinking, 'Surely by the animal sacrifice we shall obtain cattle.' Then they obtained cattle who sacrifice with the animal sacrifice. This is the first animal sacrifice, the victim sacred to Agni and Soma. This victim sacred to Agni and Soma is the breath; he who sacrifices with the victim sacred to Agni and Soma obtains cattle by the breath. When the victim sacred to Agni and Soma is led forward, it is for the production and procreation of offspring. This victim is the scorcher; the scorcher is of the animal sacrifice. He who first uses the animal sacrifice dies; he who uses it a second time dies; he who uses this very one lives. Therefore he should use this one, not the first nor the second. The head of the victim should be grasped first; if he grasped the head, he would seize its breath; therefore he should not grasp it; he should cut off the head from behind and throw it. And they say, 'He who grasps it from the middle becomes a buyer of the sacrifice; therefore he should grasp it from the middle.' For the breath is in the middle; thus he secures the breath.",
        "example": "The animal sacrifice is not about animals. It is about what you sacrifice of yourself. The victim sacred to Agni and Soma is your breath. One breath offered today. Not for result. For the offering itself. That offering obtains cattle — not literal cows, but the resources you need to live. The head not grasped first means do not sacrifice your thinking before you sacrifice your doing. The middle is the heart. Grasp from the heart means sacrifice from love, not from duty. Not obligation. Love. One sacrifice of ego today. One moment where you act not for credit, not for recognition, but because it is right. That sacrifice is the heart grasped. It secures your breath — you come alive in that moment."
    },
    10: {
        "sanskrit": "यद्वै पशुपुरोडाशं निर्वपति वज्रो वै पशुपुरोडाशो यद्वज्रं निर्वपति तेन द्विषतो भ्रातृव्यस्य वीर्यं वृङ्क्ते । यदाज्यभागौ जुहोति यद्वै प्रजापतिः पशूनसृजत तेषां ये देवान्त्समाविशंस्ते सोमार्हा अभवन् ये रक्षांसि ते अयज्ञिया ये मनुष्यान् समाविशंस्त आज्यस्य व्रीहियवानां प्रिया धामानोऽभवन् तेषामाज्यभागावभवताम् । यदाज्यभागौ जुहोति पशूनां वा एष प्रियाणि धामान्यवरुन्द्धे । अथो आज्यभागावेवाप्येते । यत्स्विष्टकृतो जुहोति वज्रो वै स्विष्टकृत् । तस्माद्य एवं वेद नास्य स्विष्टकृता पशवो ह्रियन्ते । अथो यदाज्यभागौ जुहोति तेन सर्वायुर्भवति । यदुत्तरान् प्रयाजान् जुहोति तेन सर्वं पशूनां वरुणगृहीतं प्रमुञ्चति । यदपरान् प्रयाजान् जुहोति तेन सर्वं पशूनां ब्रह्मगृहीतं प्रमुञ्चति । अथो प्राणानामेवैतद्ब्रह्मवर्चसस्य सर्वायुत्वाय सर्वाप्यायनम् ॥",
        "meaning": "When he offers the cake for the victim, the cake for the victim is the thunderbolt; when he offers the thunderbolt, he takes the power of his foe and rival. When he offers the butter-portions, Prajapati created creatures; those that entered into the gods became worthy of Soma; those that entered the Raksases became unfit for sacrifice; those that entered men became the dear forms of butter, rice, and barley. Of them the butter-portions were made. When he offers the butter-portions, he secures the dear forms of cattle. And also these two are the butter-portions. When he offers the oblation to the well-offered, the well-offered is the thunderbolt. Therefore for him who knows thus, cattle are not taken away by the well-offered. And when he offers the butter-portions, he obtains a full life. When he offers the fore-offerings, he frees all cattle from the grip of Varuna. When he offers the after-offerings, he frees all cattle from the grip of the Brahman. And also this is the full development of the breaths, of spiritual lustre, for full life.",
        "example": "Thunderbolt is your decisive action. One decision made without hesitation today. That decision takes the power of your foe — not an enemy outside, but the foe of indecision within. Butter-portions are the small joys of daily life. One small joy noticed today. Not chased. Not grasped. Noticed. That noticing secures the dear forms of cattle — the nourishment you need, not the indulgence you want. The well-offered is action done well, not perfectly. One action done well today. Done completely, not half. That action prevents cattle (your vital resources) from being taken away. Not by others. By your own incompleteness. Complete what you start. One completion today frees you from Varuna's grip (the law of consequences you cannot escape) and from Brahman's grip (the weight of spiritual expectation). Not escaping. Completing."
    }
}
# Krishna Yajurveda - Taittiriya Samhita
