KRISHNA_YAJURVEDA_K1_P3 = {
    1: {
        "sanskrit": "अग्नीषोमीयं पशुमालभेत । ब्रह्मवर्चसकामो ब्रह्मवर्चस्येव भवति योऽग्नीषोमीयं पशुमालभते । प्रजाकामः पशुकामो वा अग्नीषोमीयेन यजेत । प्रजा वै पशवो यज्ञः । प्रजननं वा एतत् प्रजननं यदग्नीषोमीयः पशुः । यदग्नीषोमीयं पशुमालभते प्रजात्या एव तत् । अग्नीषोमीयं पशुमालभेत । प्राणापानौ वा अग्नीषोमीयः पशुः । प्राणापानावेव तेनालभते । स वा एष देवो देवेषु यः प्रथमो यज्ञेभ्यो निरक्रामत् । तस्य त्रयो बन्धवः प्राणो व्यानोऽपानः । तस्य यदग्नीषोमीयं पशुमालभते प्राणापानावेव तेनालभते । व्यानं शिर एति । यद्वा एतस्य पशोः शिरश्छिनत्ति व्यानमेवास्य छिनत्ति । व्यानं वा अस्य छिनत्ति यो वैतस्य पशोः शिरश्छिनत्ति । तस्मान्न शिरश्छिन्द्यात् । पश्चाच्छिरः प्रच्छिद्य प्रहरेत् । प्राणापानावेव तेनालभते । व्यानं शिरो गच्छति ॥",
        "meaning": "Let him offer a victim to Agni and Soma. He who desires spiritual lustre becomes possessed of spiritual lustre if he offers a victim to Agni and Soma. Let him who desires offspring or cattle sacrifice with a victim to Agni and Soma. Offspring are cattle and the sacrifice. This victim sacred to Agni and Soma is for procreation; when he offers the victim to Agni and Soma, that is for procreation. The victim sacred to Agni and Soma is expiration and inspiration; verily by it he seizes expiration and inspiration. This god was the first to go forth from the sacrifices; his three bonds are expiration, through-breathing, inspiration. When he offers the victim to Agni and Soma, he seizes expiration and inspiration; the through-breathing goes to the head. When one cuts off the head of this victim, he cuts off its through-breathing. Verily he cuts off its through-breathing who cuts off the head of this victim; therefore he should not cut off the head. He should cut off the head from behind and cast it away; thus he seizes expiration and inspiration; the through-breathing goes to the head.",
        "example": "Agni (will) and Soma (clarity) together are the source of your sacrifice. One action today combining will and clarity. That action seizes expiration and inspiration — your life force itself. The head not cut means do not sacrifice your thinking. Cut from behind means release attachment to outcome, not to intention."
    },
    2: {
        "sanskrit": "प्रोक्षितः पशुरुपाकृतः । देवस्य त्वा सवितुः प्रसवेऽश्विनोर्बाहुभ्यां पूष्णो हस्ताभ्यामग्नये जुष्टं प्रोक्षामि । प्रोक्षितो यज्ञपतिं प्राणैरभ्यात्मन् । अवधूतं रक्षोऽवधूता अरातयः । यावद्वै रक्षसां यज्ञियानामनुक्ता भवन्ति तावदेनमुपजीवन्ति यद्यजमानस्य पशुम् । यदुपाकरोति देवानां प्रत्यवरोहति । यत्प्रोक्षति देवानां प्रत्यवरोहति । यत्सम्प्रैषमाह देवानां प्रत्यवरोहति । तस्मात्त्रिः प्रोक्षेत् । यद्वै पशुं त्रिः प्रोक्षति यज्ञियमेवैनं कुरुते त्रिः प्रोक्षति । इदमहं तं प्रोक्षामि योऽस्मान् द्वेष्टि यं वयं द्विष्मः । अग्नीषोमाभ्यां त्वा जुष्टं प्रोक्षामि । देवस्त्वा सविता प्रोक्षतु वसोः पवित्रेण शश्वतीभिस्तनूभिः सुपिप्पलाभिरोषधीभिः सुपिप्पलं मा करोतन । उपाकृतोऽसि । नमः प्राणाय नमोऽपानाय नमो व्यानाय नम उदानाय नमः समानाय नमः प्रजापतये । यस्ते प्राणो य आत्मनि स ते शिवतमो भूत्वा जगत्यामनु सं चर तया मा संसृज तया मा प्रजया पशुभिरन्नादेन समर्धय । यस्ते प्राणो य आत्मनि तं तेऽहं प्रजया पशुभिरन्नादेन समर्धयामि । सह प्रजया सह रायस्पोषेण पुनरस्मान् प्राणो गच्छतु ॥",
        "meaning": "The victim is consecrated, led forward. On the impulse of the god Savitr, with the arms of the Asvins, with the hands of Pusan, I sprinkle thee acceptable to Agni. The consecrated victim by its breaths approaches the sacrificer. The Raksas is shaken off, the evil spirits are shaken off. As long as the Raksases that lie in wait for the sacrifice are not removed, so long they infest the victim of the sacrificer. When he leads forward, he descends to the gods; when he sprinkles, he descends to the gods; when he utters the summons, he descends to the gods; therefore he should sprinkle thrice. When he sprinkles the victim thrice, he makes it fit for sacrifice. 'Him who hates us and whom we hate I sprinkle.' 'I sprinkle thee acceptable to Agni and Soma.' 'Let the god Savitr sprinkle thee with the filter of wealth, with thine own forms, with full-fruited plants; make me full-fruited.' 'Thou art led forward.' 'Homage to expiration, homage to inspiration, homage to through-breathing, homage to upward-breathing, homage to equal-breathing, homage to Prajapati.' 'That expiration which is in thy self, may it being most beneficent go around in the world; unite me with it; endow me with it with offspring, with cattle, with food.' 'That expiration which is in thy self, with it I endow thee with offspring, with cattle, with food.' 'May expiration return to us together with offspring, together with increase of wealth.'",
        "example": "Sprinkling is your intention made visible. One action today done with clear intention. That intention is the sprinkling. Not accidental. Intended. The Raksas shaken off is one excuse you stop making. Not by fighting. By acting. The three sprinklings are thought, word, and deed aligned. One action where you think it, say it (to yourself), and do it. Homage to the five breaths means honor your life force. One breath today breathed with full awareness."
    },
    3: {
        "sanskrit": "वपया प्रचरति । वपा वा एतस्य पशोः प्रिया तनूर्यद्वपा। यद्वपया प्रचरति प्रिययैवैनं तन्वा समर्धयति । अग्नीषोमाभ्यां वपाश्रपण्याः । अग्निर्देवता वपायाः । अग्निर्देवता वपाया इन्द्रः प्राणापानौ यो देवानां यज्ञियानामनुक्ता भवन्ति । उपांशु वपया प्रचरति । यदुच्चैः प्रचरेयुर्यज्ञियान् देवाननु ब्रूयात् । तस्मादुपांशु प्रचरेत् । यद्वा एतस्य पशोरपराध्नुवन्ति तद्वपा भवति । वपया वै देवा यज्ञस्य शिरः समारोहयन् । यद्वपया प्रचरति शिर एव तद्यज्ञस्य समारोहयति । वपया प्रचरति । पशवो वै वपा। पशव एव तत् प्रीणाति । वपया प्रचरति । वपा वा इदं सर्वं यदिदं किञ्च। सर्वमेव तत् प्रीणाति । वपया प्रचरति । वपा वै यज्ञस्य दक्षिणं बाहुम् अग्रे प्रतिमुञ्चते। दक्षिणं बाहुं यज्ञस्य समारोहयति। वपया प्रचरति। बृहस्पतये वपाश्रपण्याः । अग्नीषोमाभ्यां वपाश्रपण्याः ।",
        "meaning": "He offers the omentum. The omentum is the dear form of this victim. When he offers the omentum, he endows it with its dear form. The omentum is sacred to Agni and Soma. Agni is the deity of the omentum. He offers the omentum in a low voice. If he should offer it aloud, he would announce the sacrifice to the gods. Therefore he should offer it in a low voice. That which they fail in with this victim becomes the omentum. By the omentum the gods raised the head of the sacrifice. When he offers the omentum, he raises the head of the sacrifice. The omentum is cattle; verily he gratifies cattle. The omentum is all this whatsoever exists; verily he gratifies all. The omentum first puts on the right arm of the sacrifice; he raises the right arm of the sacrifice.",
        "example": "The omentum is the first offering — your first action of the day. One first action done before checking phone, before email, before distraction. That first action raises the head of your sacrifice. Not the body. The head — intention itself. The right arm of the sacrifice is your ability to act. One action chosen deliberately, not reactively. That action puts on the right arm of your day."
    },
    4: {
        "sanskrit": "आग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्या । आग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यया यजेत । अग्निर्वा एतस्य पशोः प्रतिबद्धः प्राणो यदाग्नेयः । तस्य यदाग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यः प्राणमेवास्य तेनालभते । आग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यया यजेत । पशून् वा एतस्य यज्ञस्याग्निरपचक्राम तानाग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्ययैवाप्याययति । तस्मादाग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यः । आग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यया यजेत । पशवो वा आग्नेयः । पशून् एव तेनालभते । आग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यया यजेत । यज्ञो वा आग्नेयः । यज्ञमेव तेनालभते । आग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यया यजेत । अग्निर्वै देवानामवमो विष्णुः परमः । तदेतौ देवौ व्यत्यासं यज्ञस्योभयतः पार्ष्ण्या गृहीत्वा तिष्ठतः । यदाग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यस्तस्मादग्निरवमो विष्णुः परमः । आग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यया यजेत । अग्निर्वै देवेभ्यो यज्ञं प्रायच्छत् । तेनाग्निः प्रायच्छत् । तस्मादाग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यः । आग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्यया यजेत । अग्नेर्वा एतस्य पशोरनुबन्धः स योऽग्नेयोऽनुबन्ध्योऽग्निमेव तेनालभते ।",
        "meaning": "The victim for the after-offering is sacred to Agni. Let him sacrifice with a victim sacred to Agni for the after-offering. Agni is the bond of this victim, the breath; with the after-offering to Agni he seizes its breath. Agni departed from the cattle of this sacrifice; with the after-offering to Agni he causes them to swell. The victim sacred to Agni is cattle; verily by it he seizes cattle. The victim sacred to Agni is the sacrifice; verily by it he seizes the sacrifice. Agni is the lowest of the gods, Visnu the highest. These two gods stand holding the sacrifice on both sides by the heel. Since the after-offering is to Agni, therefore Agni is the lowest, Visnu the highest. Agni gave the sacrifice to the gods; with that Agni gave. The after-offering is the bond of this victim to Agni; with the victim sacred to Agni he seizes Agni.",
        "example": "The after-offering is what you do after the main action. One small follow-up action today after your main task. Not abandoning. Completing. Agni is the lowest god — the most accessible fire in your hearth. Visnu is the highest — the all-pervading. Your small daily actions (Agni) and your highest values (Visnu) are not separate. One small action aligned with your highest value today. That action holds the sacrifice on both sides. Not one without the other."
    },
    5: {
        "sanskrit": "वैश्वदेवो बर्हिषः पशुः । वैश्वदेवेन बर्हिषः पशुना यजेत । प्रजापतिर्वै पशूनसृजत तानसृज्यमानान् विश्वे देवा अन्वसृज्यन्त तद्वैश्वदेवस्य वैश्वदेवत्वम् । वैश्वदेवेन बर्हिषः पशुना यजेत । प्रजापतिर्वै प्रजा असृजत ता अस्मात् सृष्टाः पराञ्चो यज्ञियाद्बर्हिषः प्राणन् ता वैश्वदेवेन बर्हिषः पशुना सम्यक् प्रत्यौहत् । यद्वैश्वदेवेन बर्हिषः पशुना यजते यज्ञियाद्बर्हिषः प्रजाः प्रत्यूह एव तत् । वैश्वदेवो बर्हिषः पशुः । बर्हिर्वै देवानां यज्ञियं प्रतिष्ठा । यद्वैश्वदेवेन बर्हिषः पशुना यजते यज्ञिय एव बर्हिषि प्रजां प्रतिष्ठापयति । वैश्वदेवेन बर्हिषः पशुना यजेत । वैश्वदेवो वा एष यः पशुः सप्तदशो देवत्या सप्तदशो वै प्रजापतिः प्रजापतिमेव तेनालभते । यद्वै प्रजापतिं पशुमालभते प्रजा एव तेन प्रजनयति । वैश्वदेवेन बर्हिषः पशुना यजेत । बर्हिर्वै देवानां यज्ञियं प्रतिष्ठा यज्ञस्य यज्ञियमासनम् । यद्वैश्वदेवेन बर्हिषः पशुना यजते यज्ञिय एव बर्हिषि यज्ञं प्रतिष्ठापयति ।",
        "meaning": "The victim for the strew is sacred to the All-gods. Let him sacrifice with the victim sacred to the All-gods for the strew. Prajapati created cattle; as they were being created, the All-gods were created after them; that is the All-god nature of the victim to the All-gods. Prajapati created creatures; they, being created, departed from him breathing forth from the sacrificial strew; with the victim sacred to the All-gods for the strew he brought them back. When he sacrifices with the victim sacred to the All-gods for the strew, he brings back the creatures from the sacrificial strew. The strew is the firm seat for the sacrifice. He who knows the victim sacred to the All-gods for the strew is seventeenfold in deity. Prajapati is seventeenfold; verily he seizes Prajapati. When he offers a victim to Prajapati, he produces offspring.",
        "example": "The strew is the ground you stand on — your foundation. One foundational value you hold. Not a goal. A value. Integrity. Kindness. Courage. That value is your strew. The All-gods are all your inner powers working together. One action from your foundational value today. That action brings all your powers together. Not scattered. Gathered. The seventeenfold nature of Prajapati means your creative source is not simple but complex. Not one answer. Many. One action that honors complexity, not reduction."
    },
    6: {
        "sanskrit": "प्राजापत्यो निरूढपशुबन्धः । प्राजापत्येन निरूढपशुबन्धेन यजेत । प्रजापतिर्वा एतस्य यज्ञस्य प्रतिष्ठा । यत्प्राजापत्यो निरूढपशुबन्धः प्रजापतिमेव तेन प्रतिष्ठां गच्छति । प्राजापत्यो निरूढपशुबन्धः । प्रजा वै प्रजापतिः । प्रजा एव तेन प्रजनयति । प्राजापत्यो निरूढपशुबन्धः । प्राजापत्या वै देवताः प्रजापतिना यज्ञः समाप्यते । प्राजापत्येन निरूढपशुबन्धेन यजेत । अग्निर्वै देवानामवमो विष्णुः परमः । तदेतौ देवौ व्यत्यासं यज्ञस्योभयतः पार्ष्ण्या गृहीत्वा तिष्ठतः । यः प्राजापत्यो निरूढपशुबन्धः स यज्ञः । प्राजापत्यो निरूढपशुबन्धः । प्रजापतिर्वा एतस्य यज्ञस्य प्रतिष्ठा । यत्प्राजापत्यो निरूढपशुबन्धः प्रजापतिमेव तेन प्रतिष्ठां गच्छति ।",
        "meaning": "The animal sacrifice is sacred to Prajapati. Let him sacrifice with the animal sacrifice sacred to Prajapati. Prajapati is the foundation of this sacrifice. Since the animal sacrifice is sacred to Prajapati, by it he goes to the foundation, Prajapati. The animal sacrifice sacred to Prajapati produces offspring. Prajapati is offspring; verily by it he produces offspring. The sacrifice is completed with Prajapati. Agni is the lowest of the gods, Visnu the highest. These two gods stand holding the sacrifice on both sides by the heel. The animal sacrifice sacred to Prajapati is the sacrifice.",
        "example": "Prajapati is your creative source. One creative act today. Not for result. For expression. That act is the animal sacrifice — not killing, but offering your small self to your larger self. Agni (will) and Visnu (preservation) hold your sacrifice on both sides. One action that uses will (Agni) and preserves what matters (Visnu). Not destroying. Offering. The foundation is not a belief. It is the act of creating itself. One creative act today founds your day. Not planning. Creating."
    },
    7: {
        "sanskrit": "पशुबन्धेन यजेत । पशवो वै पशुबन्धः । पशून् एव तेनालभते । पशुबन्धेन यजेत । यज्ञो वै पशुबन्धः । यज्ञमेव तेनालभते । पशुबन्धेन यजेत । यज्ञो वै पशुबन्धः । यद्यज्ञं पशुबन्धेन समर्धयति । पशुबन्धेन यजेत । पशवो वै पशुबन्धः । पशूनां स्तुत्यै । पशुबन्धेन यजेत । प्रजापतिर्वै पशुबन्धः । प्रजापतिमेव तेनालभते । पशुबन्धेन यजेत । प्रजापतिर्वै पशुबन्धः । प्रजा वै प्रजापतिः । प्रजा एव तेन प्रजनयति । पशुबन्धेन यजेत । पशवो वै पशुबन्धः । पशून् एव तेन प्रीणाति । पशुबन्धेन यजेत । यज्ञो वै पशुबन्धः । यज्ञमेव तेन प्रीणाति । पशुबन्धेन यजेत । यज्ञो वै पशुबन्धः । यद्यज्ञं पशुबन्धेन समर्धयति ।",
        "meaning": "Let him sacrifice with the animal sacrifice. The animal sacrifice is cattle; verily by it he seizes cattle. The animal sacrifice is the sacrifice; verily by it he seizes the sacrifice. With the animal sacrifice he perfects the sacrifice. The animal sacrifice is Prajapati; verily by it he seizes Prajapati. Prajapati is offspring; verily by it he produces offspring. With the animal sacrifice he gratifies cattle. With the animal sacrifice he gratifies the sacrifice. With the animal sacrifice he perfects the sacrifice.",
        "example": "The animal sacrifice is what you offer of yourself. One offering today of something you cling to. An opinion. A grudge. A fear. That offering seizes cattle — your scattered resources gather when you release attachment. Not holding. Releasing. Prajapati is offspring — your creative projects are born when you sacrifice what you no longer need. One project started today after releasing one old attachment. Not accumulation. Creation through release."
    },
    8: {
        "sanskrit": "यद्यज्ञे पशुरुपम्रियेत । ब्रह्मणे वरं दद्यात् । ब्रह्म वै यज्ञस्य प्रतिष्ठा । ब्रह्मण्येव तद्यज्ञं प्रतिष्ठापयति । यद्यज्ञे पशुरुपम्रियेत । आग्नेयमष्टाकपालं निर्वपेत् । अग्निर्वै यज्ञस्य मुखम् । मुख एव तद्यज्ञं प्रतिष्ठापयति । यद्यज्ञे पशुरुपम्रियेत । अग्नीषोमीयमेकादशकपालं निर्वपेत् । अग्नीषोमौ वै यज्ञस्योभयतः पार्ष्ण्या गृहीत्वा तिष्ठतः । ताभ्यामेव तद्यज्ञं प्रतिष्ठापयति । यद्यज्ञे पशुरुपम्रियेत । ब्रह्मणे वरं दद्यात् । ब्रह्म वै यज्ञस्य प्रतिष्ठा । ब्रह्मण्येव तद्यज्ञं प्रतिष्ठापयति । यद्यज्ञे पशुरुपम्रियेत । ब्रह्मणे वरं दद्यात् । यज्ञो वै ब्रह्मणे वरं ददाति । यज्ञमेव तत् समर्धयति ।",
        "meaning": "If the victim dies at the sacrifice, let him give a boon to the Brahman. The Brahman is the foundation of the sacrifice; on the Brahman he establishes the sacrifice. If the victim dies at the sacrifice, let him offer a cake on eight potsherds to Agni. Agni is the mouth of the sacrifice; in the mouth he establishes the sacrifice. If the victim dies at the sacrifice, let him offer a cake on eleven potsherds to Agni and Soma. Agni and Soma stand holding the sacrifice on both sides by the heel; by them he establishes the sacrifice. If the victim dies at the sacrifice, let him give a boon to the Brahman. The Brahman is the foundation of the sacrifice; on the Brahman he establishes the sacrifice. If the victim dies at the sacrifice, let him give a boon to the Brahman. The sacrifice gives a boon to the Brahman; thus he perfects the sacrifice.",
        "example": "If the victim dies means when your best intention fails. One failure today. Not hidden. Acknowledged. The Brahman is your higher wisdom. Give a boon to the Brahman means learn from the failure. One lesson extracted. Not wasted. That lesson perfects the sacrifice — the failure becomes part of the offering. Not erased. Included. Agni (will) and Soma (clarity) hold the sacrifice on both sides. One failure examined with both will (to continue) and clarity (to see what happened). Not one without the other."
    },
    9: {
        "sanskrit": "वपाश्रपण्यौ भवतः । बृहस्पतये वपाश्रपण्याः । अग्नीषोमाभ्यां वपाश्रपण्याः । बृहस्पतिर्वै देवानां ब्रह्मा । ब्रह्मणा ब्रह्मवर्चसेन वपामवद्यति । अग्नीषोमाभ्यां वपाश्रपण्याः । प्राणापानौ वा अग्नीषोमौ । प्राणापानाभ्यामेवास्य वपामुपरिष्टादवद्यति । यद्वै पशोरुपरिष्टाद्वपामवद्यति प्राणापानावेवास्योपरिष्टाद्धरते । प्राणापानौ वा अस्योपरिष्टाद्धरते यो वैतस्य पशोरुपरिष्टाद्वपामवद्यति । तस्मादुपरिष्टाद्वपामवद्येत् । अथो खल्वाहुः पुरस्ताद्वपामवद्येदिति । प्राणो वै पुरस्ताद्वपा । प्राणमेवास्य तेनालभते । उभयीरेव वपाश्रपण्यौ भवतः । उभयत एवास्य वपामवद्यति प्राणापानावेव तेनालभते ।",
        "meaning": "There are two omentum-pans; one for Brhaspati, one for Agni and Soma. Brhaspati is the Brahman of the gods; with the Brahman and spiritual lustre he cuts off the omentum. The omentum-pan for Agni and Soma; Agni and Soma are expiration and inspiration; with expiration and inspiration he cuts off the omentum of it above. When he cuts off the omentum of the victim above, he carries off its expiration and inspiration above. He who cuts off the omentum of the victim above carries off its expiration and inspiration above; therefore he should cut off the omentum above. But they say, 'He should cut off the omentum in front.' The omentum in front is the breath; verily by it he seizes its breath. Both omentum-pans exist; on both sides he cuts off its omentum, and thus he seizes its expiration and inspiration.",
        "description": "The two omentum-pans and the cutting off of the omentum",
        "example": "Brhaspati is the lord of speech — your inner voice of wisdom. One wise word spoken to yourself today. Not criticism. Wisdom. That word cuts off the omentum of ego. Agni and Soma are expiration and inspiration — the breath. One breath fully conscious. That breath cuts off the omentum above — the attachment to outcome. Not holding. Releasing. Both pans mean you need both wisdom (Brhaspati) and breath awareness (Agni-Soma) to make the full sacrifice. Not one without the other."
    },
    10: {
        "sanskrit": "वपया प्रचर्य पुरोडाशेन प्रचरति । पशवो वै वपा । पशून् एव तत् प्रीणाति । यज्ञो वै पुरोडाशः । यज्ञमेव तत् प्रीणाति । वपया प्रचर्य पुरोडाशेन प्रचरति । यज्ञस्यैव तत् शिरः समारोहयति । वपया प्रचर्य पुरोडाशेन प्रचरति । प्रजापतिर्वा एतस्य यज्ञस्य प्रतिष्ठा । प्रजापतिमेव तत् प्रतिष्ठां गच्छति । वपया प्रचर्य पुरोडाशेन प्रचरति । अग्निर्वै देवानामवमो विष्णुः परमः । तदेतौ देवौ व्यत्यासं यज्ञस्योभयतः पार्ष्ण्या गृहीत्वा तिष्ठतः । यद्वपया प्रचरति तदग्निरवमो यत्पुरोडाशेन तद्विष्णुः परमः । एतावेव तद्यज्ञस्योभयतः पार्ष्ण्या गृहीत्वा तिष्ठतः । वपया प्रचर्य पुरोडाशेन प्रचरति । यज्ञो वै पुरोडाशः । यज्ञमेव तत् समर्धयति ।",
        "meaning": "Having offered the omentum, he offers the cake. The omentum is cattle; verily he gratifies cattle. The cake is the sacrifice; verily he gratifies the sacrifice. Having offered the omentum, he offers the cake; thereby he raises the head of the sacrifice. Having offered the omentum, he offers the cake; Prajapati is the foundation of this sacrifice; thereby he goes to the foundation, Prajapati. Having offered the omentum, he offers the cake. Agni is the lowest of the gods, Visnu the highest. These two gods stand holding the sacrifice on both sides by the heel. With the omentum he offers to Agni the lowest, with the cake to Visnu the highest. Thus he stands holding the sacrifice on both sides by the heel. Having offered the omentum, he offers the cake; the cake is the sacrifice; thus he perfects the sacrifice.",
        "example": "First the omentum (the first offering), then the cake (the main offering). One small action first thing in the morning (omentum), then your main work (cake). That order raises the head of your sacrifice — your intention. Not random. Ordered. Agni (lowest, most accessible) and Visnu (highest, most expansive) hold your sacrifice. One action that is both small and practical (Agni) and aligned with your highest values (Visnu). Not one without the other. That action perfects the sacrifice. Not because it is grand. Because it is whole."
    }
}
